Prediciting a Countries' Happiness¶

Tutorial by Ravi Rosyidi

Motivation¶

Happiness is universally a postive emotion. One does not feel content with life without some form of happiness. Personally, with quaratine shutting down my social life, exposing corrupt politicans, and even destroying many countries economics, I wondered if there was any correlation between those factors and my lack of happiness. It's also not just my happiness but many of my friends, teachers, and co-workers. In fact, society as a whole has, in my opinion, been frustrated, stressed, and unhappy with the world. I would like to know the factors that influnece a societies happiness and differetiate each factor to better understand what drivers a society. After all, happiness is the emotion that everyone in the world would like to have. It been linked to better decision-making and improved creativity. Not to mention the thousand other benefits to a society as a whole. In this tutorial, we will investigate the causes of a countries happiness and determine the most influential factors that dictate a countries' happiness.

Source and Dataset¶

I choose the database website kaggle and more specifically, the happiness report 2021 to gather my information. This website contains many different datasets from a wide range of topics. Some of the datasets contain monthly, yearly, and even overall statistics. For this tutorial, I have chosen the 2021 happiness report because it contains datapoints such as GDP per capita and healthy life expectancy in order to create a thorough hypothesis and conclusion. It contains enough overall information about the country that can help to determine a cause of ones low or high happiness score.

First thing to do on our list is to grab the dataset. Fortunately, since its a csv file, pandas has a function called read_csv that allows us to convert the csv file into a pandas dataframe. For this instance, we extract the information from the report and store it in our variable called data

Now that our table is in a tidy form, here is a formal definition of each column

  1. Country Name: The name of the country

  2. Regional Indicator: Location at which country resides

  3. Happiness Score: Score given to country based on its happiness

  4. Standard Deviation of Happiness Score: STD of Happiness Score

  5. Logged GDP per capita: A countries economic output with respect to population

  6. Social Support: Extent at which areas such as culture and family support the individual

  7. Healthy life expectancy: Expected Life Expectancy of each person in the country

  8. Freedom to make life choices: Extent of the freedom in the country

  9. Generosity: How generous the population is

  10. Perceptions of Corruption: Extent at which the people trust the government

Data Visualization and Analysis¶

Firstly, what we want to do is determine the most influential factors to a countries happiness. Thus we have to make charts and analyze. To visual graphs we will be using functions such as seaborn.lmplot to plot linear regressions, seaborn.scatterplot for scatterplot grouping, and plt.subplot to plot multiple graphs at once.

Happiness Score with Respect to GDP Per Capita¶

First we shall make a chart ploting each countries score with respect to their GDP

In [21]:
# Plottoing the scatter plot as well as the linear regression line of 
# countries happiness with respect to its GDP
seaborn.lmplot(data = data, x="Logged GDP per capita", 
                    y="Happiness Score", )
plt.title("Linear Regression Model of Happiness vs GDP")
Out[21]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Linear Regression Model of Happiness vs GDP')

What we can determine based on the model and linear regression line is that GDP and Happiness score have a positive relationship with eachother. As GDP increases, happiness score also increases. Now for extra analysis we will also look at the graph again, however, this time each plot is grouped based on region and we remove the regression line for visual clarity.

In [22]:
# Plotting the scatterplot without the linear regression line
# and with each plot grouped 
seaborn.scatterplot(data = data, x="Logged GDP per capita", 
                    y="Happiness Score", hue = "Regional indicator")

plt.title("Happiness vs GDP Characterized by Region")

# Moving the legend out of the graph for clarity
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.01, 1),
           borderaxespad=0)
Out[22]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7f6b0d4aa8b0>

What we can notice from this graph is that each region of the world generally has its own GDP range. Western Europian countries are rich in GDP but also have the highest happiness scores followed by North America in both GDP and happiness score. Near the lower area of the list are Sub-Saharan Africa with a wide range of GDP and towards the lower happiness scores. However, GDP is far from the only factor and its important we look at the other causes while keeping region in the back of our minds.

Conclusion on the influence of GDP on Happiness Score¶

Its clear that GDP has a significant influence on a countries Happiness. This is apparent from the near linear shape of each countries plot with respect to GDP and happiness. Basically saying that the graph itself is a linear graph. It also important to note that countries within the same region will also have around the same GDP and as a result around the same happiness score. Although there are some outliers in the mix, it looks to be uniform. Western Europe being the region leading in both GDP and Happiness score follow by the North America and ANZ. To determine a countries happiness score, we need to look at the other factors as they may have more of a direct impact.

Again we see that Western Europe have the highest happiness scores but not always having the absolute highest social support. Some countries even hitting as low as around 5.2 while having the highest social support scores.

Conclusion on the influence of Social Support on Happiness¶

Its clear from the linear regression line of the original graph that overall, social support does indeed have a positive relationship with a countries happiness. However, as we began to dive deeper into the data, we found that your social support may not have as much linear impact as we have thought. This trend reminds me of the law of dimishing returns which basically states that as you push the boundaries on your input you get less and less ouput. In this case, if you have low social support then any increase in social support will have a large increase in happiness score. On the other hand, if you already have a high social support score, any further increase in social support will yield lesser increase in happiness score.

Here we can see that some regions relative shows that high health expectancy is not indicative of high happiness. We can see that from East Asia regional boxplot as well as the Sub-Saharan African region boxplot. Starting with East Asia, we see that the bulk of East Asian countries have near the highest life expectancty. However, looking back at life expectancy per region we can see that atleast four other regions have higher happiness scores. This idea is flipped when we look at the Sub-Saharan Africa region. We can see that their life expectancy is far below any other regions, around ten years shorter than the second worst regions. However, when we look at their happiness score they are higher than what you would expect in relation to other countries happiness score. This however, could simply be due to external factors, such as culture, seeing that eight other regions have expected happiness scores (mid/high life expectancy = mid/high happiness scores).

Conclusion on the influence of life expectancy on happiness¶

Overall, life expectancy has a linear and positive impact on a countries happiness. Based on the original graph showing a visual linear relationship with what looks to be no dimishing return, we can say that life expectancy has a large impact on happiness. Even though we found anomlies from the second graph pertaining to East Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa, eight out of the ten regions were plotted as expected relative to eachother postion. Therefore, it isn't strong enough evidence to disprove the fact that life expectancy has a large and positive impact on happiness.

What we can see from finding the range (min - max) is that there is a wide range of happiness scores for countries with some of the highest freedom scores. Conclusion on the influence of freedom on Happiness¶

Seeing that there are many countries with exceptionally high freedom scores yet have a wide range of happiness scores, it is difficult to say that freedom has a strong positive impact on happiness. Countries in Sub-Saharan Africa have incredibly high freedom scores, yet they score near the bottom in happiness. This tells us that there are other factors which are more influential to a countries happiness. For example, Sub-Saharan Africa have low GDP compared to other countries but some also have high freedom scores. Yet Sub-Saharan Africa have some of the lowest happiness scores. This tells us that GDP has a much stronger impact than freedom does on happiness

In [123]:
# Calculate the linear regression line based on generosity and happiness score
model = LinearRegression().fit(data['Generosity'].values.reshape(-1,1), data['Happiness Score'])

# I then printed out the model to understand it
print("Y = " + str(model.coef_[0]) + "x + " + str(model.intercept_))

Y = -0.12687827965307963x + 5.530918721338137

Conclusion on the influence of generosity on happiness¶

Based on the linear regression line we can clearly see that generosity does not have a linear nor positive impact. In fact, when we calculated the linear regression line we can see that an increase in generosity has a decrease in happiness score. This is shown by the coefficient -0.12687 on the linear regression equation we calculated out. Based on these findings, we can conlcude that all the other factors we have analyzed today have a much larger impact on a countries happiness than generosity.

Before we make any analysis, it's important to note that high scores of perceptions of corruptions means that the public believe with high certainty that the government is corrupt. Not that the government is corrput, only the belief of the citizens. Therefore, in a way we should be looking at this graph backwards. High perceptions of corruptions is bad and lower values are good. Therefore, we expect that the relationship between happiness and corruption are inverted (expectation: high herception = low happiness).

What we find from the graph is a mixed bag. There are some countries with high happiness scores yet the people also believe that the government is corrupt. Yet on the other side, countries believe that the government is honorable and as expected they have some of the highest happiness scores. Even though the linear regression line shows a positive impact of (low) corruption on (high) happiness, there is high uncertainty as the corruption decreases as shown by the lighter shade of blue on the line. This basically means that compared to high perceptions of corruptions, the linear regression line isn't entirely confident with its analysis. For this instance, we want to take a look at the bulk of the data because we want more evidence to back up our analysis. Sure a few countries (outliers) with low corruption have high happiness. Most of the world has high corruption and still high happiness.

Conclusion on the influence of corruption on happiness¶

Based on both analysis of the bulk of the data and the orignal graph, we can see that many a governments corruption does have a slight impact on the countries happiness. This is shown from seeing Western European countries having low percetion of corruption and having some of the absolute highest happiness scores. On the otherside, countries with high perceptions of corruption are seen to have both extremely low and high happiness scores. However, these high happiness score countries have trouble getting past a score of 7. This can be in part due to the high corruption scores that these countries have. Countries with low corruption scores have all passed a happiness score of 7. Therefore, yes corruption does have an impact on happiness but it is slight.

Overall Conclusion and Final Thoughts¶

We have determined that a countries happiness is mainly dependent on (in order on decreasing influence) GDP per capita, life expectancy, and social support. Other factors such as freedom, generosity, and corruption are shown to have much less impact. Freedom having more impact than both generosity and corruption. Generosity having a negative impact on a countries happiness score. While corruption has shows to have impact on happiness but it shown to have little impact (High corruption does not always mean low happiness scores).

This does help explain the fact that COVID-19 decreasing overall societal happiness. It is in part due to the main factors that influence a countries happiness. Global economic trade has declined significanly while a nations economy plumetts due to covid. Unbeknownst, to me a countries GDP heavily affects the socities health. A declining and weak economy will result in an unhappy countries. Also, social life has also been nearly shutoff as a result of covid and social support has a strong influence on a countries happiness. Now that the economy is on a stronger recovery and social life has begun to get back to normal, I feel happier as a result. This was due to the main factors that influence societies happiness as a whole which were GDP (tied to economy) and social support (tied to social life).
